NAME
       ft_substr - allocate and return a substring

SYNOPSIS
       #include <stdlib.h>

       char *ft_substr(const char *s, unsigned int start, size_t len);

DESCRIPTION
       The ft_substr() function allocates (with malloc(3)) and returns a substring from
       the string 's'. The substring begins at index 'start' and is of maximum size 'len'.

PARAMETERS
       s      The string from which to create the substring.

       start  The start index of the substring in the string 's'.

       len    The maximum length of the substring.

RETURN VALUE
       The ft_substr() function returns the substring if the allocation is successful.
       If the allocation fails, it returns NULL.

EXTERNAL FUNCTIONS
       malloc(3) - allocate dynamic memory

NOTES
       The caller is responsible for freeing the allocated memory using free(3) when
       it is no longer needed.

EXAMPLES
       char *substring = ft_substr("Hello, World!", 7, 5);
       // substring is now "World!"

